paragraphs.title: First some do some clean up steps and load seismology data into hadoop.
paragraphs.text:
%sh
cd /tmp
if [ -e /tmp/GEM-GHEC-v1.txt ]
then
    rm -f /tmp/GEM-GHEC-v1.txt
fi
if [ -e /tmp/isc-gem-cat.zip ]
then
    rm -f /tmp/isc-gem-cat.zip
fi
if [ -e /tmp/isc-gem-cat.csv ]
then
    rm -f /tmp/isc-gem-cat.csv
fi 

if hadoop fs -stat /tmp/isc-gem-cat.csv
then
   hadoop fs -rm  /tmp/isc-gem-cat.csv
fi
if hadoop fs -stat /tmp/GEM-GHEC-v1.txt
then
   hadoop fs -rm  /tmp/GEM-GHEC-v1.txt
fi

wget https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/114020/zeppelin-snapshots/datasets/earthquake/GEM-GHEC-v1.txt
wget https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/114020/zeppelin-snapshots/datasets/earthquake/isc-gem-cat.zip
unzip isc-gem-cat.zip
hadoop fs -put GEM-GHEC-v1.txt /tmp
hadoop fs -put isc-gem-cat.csv /tmp
echo "done"

%md 
## Now lets run a machine learning algorithm to predict ... the probabilty of a magnitude 6.0 or higher.
### We'll logistic regression classification

result.msg:
Now lets run a machine learning algorithm to predict … the probabilty of a magnitude 6.0 or higher.

We'll logistic regression classification

paragraphs.text:
%md
## First import various Spark libaries

result.msg: First import various Spark libaries

paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.mllib.linalg.Vectors
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Bucketizer
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.PCA
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.LogisticRegression
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Binarizer

result.msg:
import org.apache.spark.mllib.linalg.Vectors
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Bucketizer
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.PCA
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.LogisticRegression
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Binarizer

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Let's look at a row of the earthquake data and create a dataframe (with year instead of full date).

result.msg: Let's look at a row of the earthquake data and create a dataframe (with year instead of full date).

paragraphs.text:
earthQuake.show(1)
val eq2 = earthQuake.selectExpr("id", "substr(date,1,4) as year", "lat", "lon", "depth", "mag", "munc").toDF

paragraphs.title: Spark likes numeric types. Cast all columns to double
paragraphs.text:
val df = eq2.select(eq2("id").cast("double"),
eq2("year").cast("double"),
eq2("lat").cast("double"),
eq2("lon").cast("double"),
eq2("depth").cast("double"),
eq2("mag").cast("double"),
eq2("munc").cast("double"))

df.show(3)

paragraphs.title: Now create training and testing data sets.  (60% for training and 40% for testing)
paragraphs.text: val Array(training, testing) = df.randomSplit(Array(0.6, 0.4))

result.msg:
training: org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame = [id: double, year: double, lat: double, lon: double, depth: double, mag: double, munc: double]
testing: org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame = [id: double, year: double, lat: double, lon: double, depth: double, mag: double, munc: double]

paragraphs.title: We'll use a VectorAssembler to combine many features into one feature column (logistic regression likes that)
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler
val assembler = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("id", "year", "lat", "lon", "depth", "mag", "munc"))
  .setOutputCol("featureSet")

result.msg:
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler
assembler: org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler = vecAssembler_4f946bd91270

paragraphs.title: Set the binary threshold to Richter scale Magnitude of 6.0
paragraphs.text: val binaryClassifier = new Binarizer().setInputCol("mag").setOutputCol("binaryLabel").setThreshold(6.0)

result.msg: binaryClassifier: org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Binarizer = binarizer_0041aad9221c

paragraphs.title: Create a logistic regression model and set some parameters
paragraphs.text: val lr = new LogisticRegression().setMaxIter(20).setRegParam(0.2).setElasticNetParam(0.8).setLabelCol("binaryLabel").setFeaturesCol("featureSet")

result.msg: lr: org.apache.spark.ml.classification.LogisticRegression = logreg_d811cec54c64

paragraphs.title: Chain everything together with a Spark Pipeline (great way to organize steps)
paragraphs.text:
val pipeline = new Pipeline()
  .setStages(Array(assembler, binaryClassifier, lr))

result.msg: pipeline: org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline = pipeline_5f5e3e9d6b33

paragraphs.title: Train the model
paragraphs.text: val model = pipeline.fit(training)

result.msg: model: org.apache.spark.ml.PipelineModel = pipeline_5f5e3e9d6b33

paragraphs.title: Make predictions
paragraphs.text: val prediction = model.transform(testing)

result.msg: prediction: org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame = [id: double, year: double, lat: double, lon: double, depth: double, mag: double, munc: double, featureSet: vector, binaryLabel: double, rawPrediction: vector, probability: vector, prediction: double]

paragraphs.title: Display the results
paragraphs.text: prediction.select("prediction", "binaryLabel", "mag").show(10)

%md
##How well did we do? We need to quantify the error.

%md
## Let's create a dataframe that just identifies the correct and incorrect predictions.    
###(1 is correct and 0 is incorrect)

result.msg:
Let's create a dataframe that just identifies the correct and incorrect predictions.

(1 is correct and 0 is incorrect)

paragraphs.text:
val matches = udf((A : Int, B: Int) => {
    if (A+B == 1) 0
    else 1
})

val total = prediction.count
val rightWrong = prediction.withColumn("matches", matches($"prediction", $"binaryLabel")).groupBy("matches").count.toDF
rightWrong.registerTempTable("rightWrong")
rightWrong.show
